::: {.info-block}
&#128269; **Key Findings**

- Over the last century, most job growth has occurred in counties connected to the Interstate system.

- From Interstate planning documents, I discover an overlooked natural experiment and discern that many counties are non-randomly exposed to this exogenous shock to Interstate access. Adapting Borusyak & Hull’s (2023) recentered instrument, I use predicted counterfactual networks to recover quasi-experimental variation from this planning shock.

- Among counties between major population hubs that as-good-as-randomly gained access, Interstates increased employment only where agriculture was initially important.
:::



# Raw Data & Employment Growth Regression

### Raw Employment Growth Data

:::: {.cr-section layout="overlay-right"}
In recent work, Dustin Frye assembles a new and wonderfully frequent county-level employment panel, which is invaluable for this research. He creates this panel by compiling data from the Census Bureau's County Business Patterns (CBP) across three different sources. The marker shape denotes the CBP source. Data points denoted by &times; are hand-collected from archives, &#9679; are from ICPSR and &#9675; are from data published by the US Census Bureau. [@cr-fullSampleEmpLevels]



To examine the relationship between employment growth and Interstate access, I split counties into two groups; treatment and control. I classify counties within 25km of an Interstate highway as the *treatment group* and the remainder constitute the *control group*. [@cr-splitEmpLevels]


It looks like most employment growth during the last century was concentrated in the treatment counties. Counties that gained Interstate access experienced exponential-looking employment growth. However, consistent with concerns of selection bias, these counties began with higher baseline employment and were possibly already growing faster. [@cr-splitEmpLevels]

Before thinking about the causal effect of Interstate access, I specify a regression model to capture the divergence between treatment and control counties. In the analysis that follows, I exclude the early outliers from decennial years, which appear inconsistent with other sources. [@cr-splitEmpLevels]

