### Constructing a Recentered Instrument for US Counties

:::: {.cr-section layout="overlay-right"}

I extend this idea to construct a recentered instrument for $\text{Treatment}_c$, the indicator for a county being within 25km of an Interstate highway. [@cr-basemap]

The discontintuity implied a natural experiment; there was a set of counties near the cutoff that were plausibly randomly targeted by Interstate planners. To predict which counties these were, I estimate a probability model that incorporates other planning considerations - such as elevation, surface water, and military/manufacturing importance. The map shows the results of this prediction. Near-cutoff 'coin-flip' counties are in red and above-cutoff counties that would have been targeted regardless are blue. [@cr-compliersAndAlwaysTakersMap]

I select red counties that did in fact have populations above 50,000 and draw a straight-line network to connect them. Specifically, I use a proximity graph to predict an engineer's optimal network. [@cr-ivBetaSkeleton]

Analogous to the _actual treatment_ stylized example, an $\text{UnadjustedIV}_c$ is an indicator that equals 1 if a county is within 25km of the predicted network. Lying within 25km of this predicted network is theoretically (and statistically) a good predictor of $\text{Treatment}_c$. [@cr-unadjustedIV]

Then, by permuting which red counties get targetted, I simulate 50 predicted counterfactual networks. [@cr-counterfactualBetaSkeletons]

The share of predicted counterfactual networks that lie within 25km of a county is the expected instrument. [@cr-expectedIV]

And subtracting the expected instrument from the unadjusted instruments produces a recentered instrument. [@cr-recenteredIV]

It was a lot of work to get here and the _correct_ modelling choices are not obvious. But, ultimately, the recentered instrument is only useful if it satisfies the statistical properties of a valid instrumental variable. Recall the (testable) goal of constructing a variable that (1) predicts which counties were more likely to receive Interstate access, but (2) is not correlated with underlying location fundamentals or other unobserved factors that shape local labor market growth. [@cr-recenteredIV]

